Nick Scholfield will ride Spring Heeled in the Grand National after Paul Nicholls decided not to commit to running Sam Winner, the horse Scholfield was originally expected to ride.  Scholfield will travel to Ireland to meet Spring Heeled at Jim Culloty's stable on Friday, while Culloty's other National runner, Lord Windermere, will be ridden by Robbie McNamara.  The Grand National will also see Soll, trained by David Pipe, guaranteed a run at the bottom of the weights after Double Ross was ruled out.
Columbia University faculty members have defended Dr. Mehmet Oz, stating that his work at the university is stellar despite criticism of his talk show tactics. While acknowledging that Oz's on-air "Ozisms" may have sullied the university's reputation, they argue that his contributions as a doctor outweigh these concerns. The faculty members suggest that instead of forcing Oz to resign, a disclaimer should be added to his show, clarifying that his opinions are not necessarily evidence-based or endorsed by Columbia University.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own honey, produced in her Wiltshire garden, with all proceeds going to charity. The honey, priced at £20 per jar, is part of a growing trend for gourmet honey, with sales of high-end varieties increasing significantly. The article reviews various gourmet honeys, including the Duchess's, comparing their taste, texture, and price, concluding that while some are truly exceptional, others may not justify their premium price tag.
Aubrey de Grey, a biomedical theorist, believes that aging is a curable disease and that with the right technologies, humans could live for hundreds or even thousands of years. He has gained support from Silicon Valley billionaires who are interested in extending human lifespan, but his theories have also been met with skepticism from many academics. De Grey argues that aging is caused by cellular decay and that future technologies will allow us to repair and replace damaged cells, effectively reversing the aging process.
Scientists have developed a new catalyst that significantly improves the efficiency of hydrogen production from water, minimizing energy losses in the process. This breakthrough could make hydrogen fuel more readily available and cost-effective, enabling the storage of renewable energy sources like solar and wind power. The new catalyst is highly efficient at splitting water into hydrogen and oxygen, paving the way for a cleaner and more sustainable energy future.
A study suggests that the popular Fisher-Price magnetic alphabet toys from the 1970s and 1980s may have influenced the color-letter associations of a generation of synesthetes. Researchers found that a significant portion of synesthetes born after the toy's introduction had color-letter pairings that matched the toy's design, while those born before the toy's release did not. This suggests that exposure to the toy may have led to learned synaesthesia, where external stimuli influence the involuntary sensory connections experienced by individuals with this neurological condition.
Hannah Overton, a Texas mother who spent seven years in prison for the murder of her adopted son, has been cleared of all charges. The district attorney, after reviewing the case and re-interviewing witnesses, decided to drop the charges due to a myriad of factors, including the possibility of ineffective counsel at her original trial. Overton's conviction was overturned last year due to ineffective counsel, and the new details that emerged during the appeal process led to the dismissal of the charges.
Mary Cartwright, a 91-year-old great-grandmother, revisited the Drakelow Shadow Factory, a secret underground factory where she worked during World War II. Cartwright, who was only 20 at the time, spent two years testing metal for Bristol aircraft engines in the factory's underground laboratory, working as the only woman in her department.  The factory, built in 1943, was one of 26 "shadow" sites established to mass produce engines and parts for military aircraft and tanks, ensuring production could continue even if bombed.  Cartwright found it "strange" to see the once bustling factory so quiet, reflecting on her time working there and the vital role it played in the war effort.
Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas, two top-ranked featherweight fighters, will face off in a fight that could determine the next challenger for the title, currently held by Conor McGregor. Both fighters have previously lost to Jose Aldo, but Mendes believes he is a better fighter overall and hopes a dominant win will earn him a third fight against Aldo. Lamas, meanwhile, is focused on performing well and believes a title shot will come if he continues to win.
An explosion at a chemical plant in Zhangzhou, China, injured six people and sparked a large fire. The plant produces paraxylene (PX), a chemical used in textiles and known to be carcinogenic. The fire, which occurred at an oil storage facility, is now under control, and authorities are investigating the cause of the explosion.
The MGM Grand is preparing for the biggest boxing event in its history, the fight between Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao, expecting over 100,000 people to attend. The hotel is taking extensive measures to ensure the safety of the crowd, including multiple exit routes, restricted access to the arena, and a coordinated effort between security personnel and law enforcement.  The MGM Grand is also maximizing its non-gaming revenue by offering various entertainment options and charging for access to the weigh-in and closed-circuit television broadcasts of the fight.
Samantha Cameron, the Prime Minister's wife, made her first solo appearance of the general election campaign by visiting a Ukip stronghold in Rochester and Strood, a seat held by a former Conservative MP who defected to Ukip. This visit is seen as a statement of intent from the Conservatives, who are desperate to win back the seat. Mrs. Cameron is expected to make more political interventions in the coming weeks, supporting her husband's bid to remain as Prime Minister.
The fatal shooting of Walter Scott by police officer Michael Slager in North Charleston, South Carolina, has sparked outrage and calls for police reform. The community alleges that the police department routinely dismisses complaints of misconduct, and that Slager's history of excessive force complaints was ignored.  The incident highlights a broader issue of police brutality and the lack of accountability for officers, with experts citing factors such as training, military experience, and legal system biases that contribute to a "warrior mentality" among some officers.  The release of a bystander's video showing Slager shooting Scott in the back as he ran away has further fueled public anger and calls for justice.
The Liberal Democrats are facing a significant decline in support and are expected to lose a large number of seats in the upcoming election. Despite this, they believe they can still hold the balance of power and form a coalition government with either Labour or the Conservatives. The party is focusing its campaign on a small number of marginal seats where they believe they have a chance of winning, effectively running 60 by-elections across the country.
Harry Redknapp, the former QPR manager, has turned down a lucrative offer to coach abroad, stating that he is only interested in the right job. He is open to returning to management, particularly if it involves helping a club rise through the ranks or mentoring a younger coach. Redknapp is also a strong supporter of the Men United campaign, which aims to raise awareness of prostate cancer, a cause close to his heart after losing a close friend to the disease.
Moose Toys, a global toy company based in Melbourne, Australia, has created a unique and innovative work environment that fosters creativity and collaboration. The company's headquarters features a playful and stimulating atmosphere with amenities like a beanstalk meeting room, a basketball court, and a table tennis table, encouraging employees to take breaks and engage in activities that spark new ideas. Moose Toys prioritizes employee well-being and engagement, offering social events, employee recognition programs, and opportunities for professional development, creating a strong sense of community and fostering a passionate and dedicated workforce.
A high-speed passenger train derailed near Split, Croatia, on Friday, resulting in at least six fatalities and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from Zagreb to Split when it left the tracks approximately 12 miles from its destination. Croatian police have initiated an investigation to determine the cause of the derailment.
An SBS journalist, Scott McIntyre, was fired for his controversial tweets criticizing Anzac Day and accusing Australian soldiers of war crimes.  Geoff Winestock, a senior writer for the Australian Financial Review, defended McIntyre's right to free speech and went further by calling Anzacs "racist yobs" and Anzac Day a "death cult."  The incident sparked outrage on social media, with many users calling for McIntyre's dismissal and criticizing SBS for its initial response, which was seen as a "token apology."
In the first week of the UK election campaign, Labour received £1.9 million in donations, with 84% coming from three trade unions, including a £1 million donation from Unite. The Conservatives received £500,000, with a quarter coming from donors with links to hedge funds. Critics have accused Labour of being beholden to its union donors, while the TaxPayers' Alliance has criticized both parties for making unrealistic spending pledges.
A judge sentenced a burglar who sexually assaulted a young teacher in her home to a three-year community order, sparking outrage from victim support groups. The judge acknowledged the victim's psychological trauma but deemed the sentence appropriate due to the defendant's early plea and time spent in remand. The decision has been criticized as insufficient punishment for the serious nature of the crime, with advocates arguing that victims deserve justice and offenders should receive sentences that reflect the severity of their actions.
The shooting of Walter Scott, an unarmed black man, by a white police officer in South Carolina has sparked outrage and grief among celebrities on social media.  Many celebrities, including Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Questlove, expressed their sadness and anger over the incident, which was captured on video and showed the officer shooting Scott multiple times in the back as he ran away.  The officer, Michael Slager, has been charged with murder and could face the death penalty.
Six gay men were killed in two separate incidents in Baghdad within 10 days, with relatives disowning them and tribal members carrying out the shootings. The killings followed a tribal meeting where the victims were condemned, and a cafe frequented by gay men in Sadr City was also set on fire. The Interior Ministry official who confirmed the incidents declined to be identified due to restrictions on speaking to the media.
A rare, pink crocodile Hermes Birkin bag embellished with rubies has been listed for sale on Vestiaire Collective for £140,000, making it potentially Britain's most expensive handbag. The bag is made-to-measure and so exclusive that it cannot be purchased in stores, making it a highly sought-after collector's item. The bag's value is attributed to the brand's reputation for quality craftsmanship, limited production, and the use of rare materials, which have led to a significant increase in value over time.
World heavyweight boxing champion Wladimir Klitschko is preparing for a title defense against Bryant Jennings on April 25th, but his focus remains on the ongoing conflict in his native Ukraine.  Klitschko, deeply affected by the crisis, expresses his shock and anger at the Russian aggression and the loss of life in his country.  Despite the turmoil, Klitschko remains hopeful for Ukraine's future, believing that with international support, the country can achieve a democratic future and avoid a return to a Soviet-era dictatorship.
Bruce Jenner is set to release an eight-episode docu-series on E! detailing his transition into a woman, but his children are reportedly concerned about the level of personal details he will reveal. While Jenner's children are supportive of his journey, they fear the docu-series might detract from the positive impact of his Diane Sawyer interview and urge him to complete the process privately. Despite these concerns, Jenner is committed to the project, believing it will educate and create empathy for the transgender community.
Robert Downey Jr. walked out of an interview with Channel 4 news presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy after being asked about his past drug use. This incident is one of many examples of celebrities who have abruptly ended interviews when asked personal questions, including Naomi Campbell, Robert Pattinson, and Justin Bieber.  The article highlights the tension that can arise when interviewers delve into sensitive topics, demonstrating the delicate balance between probing for interesting content and respecting the privacy of celebrities.
ISIS militants have taken control of the Yarmouk refugee camp in Damascus, Syria, leading to widespread atrocities and the displacement of thousands of residents.  A young boy, Amjad Yaaqub, witnessed ISIS fighters playing football with a severed head, highlighting the brutality of the group.  Refugees who fled the camp describe witnessing horrific acts, including the killing of children in front of their parents, and express fear and despair over the situation.
Millwall defeated Wigan Athletic 2-0 in a heated Championship match, securing a crucial victory in their fight against relegation. The game was marred by three red cards, including one for Wigan's Martyn Waghorn for a senseless kick, and saw Millwall's Jimmy Abdou score his first goal in six seasons, a moment that proved decisive. The win keeps Millwall's hopes of survival alive, while Wigan's chances of staying in the Championship appear increasingly slim.
British workers spend an average of £1,840 a year on takeaway lunches, but could save up to £1,300 by preparing their meals at home. The article suggests simple and delicious lunch options like cheese, crackers, and charcuterie, as well as more elaborate recipes like steamed Chinese buns and Vietnamese banh mi sandwiches. The article also provides budget-friendly recipes for a feta, vegetable and rice bake, crispy mash hash, pea and ham frittata, and spring chicken casserole.
Natural World Safaris is offering a unique seven-day trip to Russia's Durminskoye Reserve, where tourists can stay in the natural habitat of the endangered Siberian tiger. The trip includes opportunities to track the tigers, set camera traps, and learn from conservationist Alexander Batalov, who has dedicated his life to protecting the species. While sightings of the elusive tigers are not guaranteed, guests will be immersed in their habitat, gaining valuable insights into their lives and contributing to conservation efforts.
A 24-year-old Algerian man, Sid Ahmed Ghlam, was arrested in Paris after being linked to the murder of a young woman and a foiled plot to attack churches. Ghlam, who was under surveillance by intelligence services, had been in contact with a man in Syria who instructed him to target a church. Police found weapons, jihadi literature, and evidence of his plans in his apartment, along with DNA evidence linking him to the murder.
Researchers have conducted the first comprehensive study of the microbiome of an uncontacted Amazonian tribe, the Yanomami, revealing a remarkably diverse bacterial ecosystem. The study highlights the significant impact of modern lifestyles and diets on our microbiomes, suggesting that the Yanomami's unique bacterial composition could hold potential benefits for modern society. The findings also raise ethical concerns about the past collection of Yanomami blood samples without their informed consent, emphasizing the importance of respecting indigenous communities and their cultural practices.
Protests against "racist" historical figures in South Africa have led to the vandalization of numerous statues, including those of British colonialists, monarchs, and Afrikaner leaders. The removal of a statue of Cecil John Rhodes from the University of Cape Town, following weeks of student protests, sparked further demonstrations and counter-protests, highlighting the ongoing debate about South Africa's colonial past and its legacy. While the government supports the removal of colonial symbols, it does not condone violence, and the situation has raised concerns about potential racial tensions.
Lizzi Crawford, a mother of six, lost over seven stone after a child on a bus mistook her for being pregnant, prompting her to change her unhealthy lifestyle.  Lizzi, who previously enjoyed takeaways and boozy nights out, now attends fitness classes and cooks healthier meals, attributing her success to the support of other women at the gym.  The weight loss has not only improved her physical health but also boosted her mental well-being and allowed her to spend more time with her children.
Nafir Afzal, a former senior prosecutor, warns that hundreds of British teenagers view ISIS as pop idols, comparing their appeal to that of One Direction and Justin Bieber. He argues that this "jihadimania" is a serious threat, potentially leading to another 7/7 attack, and calls for a new approach to counter radicalization, including recruiting young Muslim role models to mentor vulnerable youth. Afzal believes that the current strategy, which he describes as "stale," is ineffective and that a community-led approach is crucial to prevent further radicalization.
Paul Downton has been sacked as managing director of the England and Wales Cricket Board following England's disastrous performance at the World Cup. The decision was unanimous, with the ECB citing the need for a new structure that prioritizes performance and accountability.  Downton's position has been replaced with a new role, director of England cricket, which will focus solely on performance and potentially lead to changes in the coaching and selection staff.
James Haskell, a rugby player for the London Wasps, posted a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram to celebrate the release of the new Avengers movie. Haskell, who has played rugby in France, Japan, and New Zealand, returned to Wasps in 2012 after a stint with the Highlanders in New Zealand. Since his return, Haskell has surpassed 100 appearances for Wasps and has become a key member of the England national team.
Good Morning Britain launched a campaign called #SelfieEsteem, encouraging celebrities and viewers to post unfiltered selfies to promote body positivity. The campaign aims to combat the pressure to look perfect on social media, as a survey revealed that women take an average of six selfies before posting one online. The initiative has received positive responses from celebrities like Susanna Reid, Josie Gibson, and Piers Morgan, who shared their unfiltered selfies and spoke about their own experiences with low self-esteem.
Imran Uddin, a university student, was jailed for four months after admitting to hacking into university computers and changing his exam grades. He used keyboard spying devices to steal staff passwords and then accessed their accounts to alter his marks, including raising one grade from a lower second to a first. The judge sentenced Uddin to jail to deter others from similar actions, emphasizing the potential damage to public confidence in the degree system.
Hillary Clinton enjoyed a relaxing stroll with her husband Bill in Chappaqua, New York, while her campaign vans received a thorough cleaning and inspection.  Clinton will resume her campaign trail in New Hampshire, holding roundtable discussions with local businesses and community members.  Despite her recent efforts to connect with "everyday Americans," Clinton continues to face criticism for her wealth and perceived disconnect from the working class.
Six Leeds United players withdrew from the squad on the eve of a match against Charlton, citing injuries, causing further chaos at the club.  The players' actions were met with criticism from former Leeds captain Trevor Cherry, who called for them to be sacked.  The incident is just the latest in a series of turbulent events at Elland Road, which has seen manager Neil Redfearn's position become increasingly precarious and the club's president, Massimo Cellino, banned from the club.
Natalie Bennett, leader of the Green Party, has distanced herself from the controversial blog posts of her boyfriend, Jim Jepps, who has written about topics such as rape fantasies and paedophilia. Jepps's blog posts have caused a stir, with the Green Party stating they do not endorse his views and are not associated with them. Bennett has declined to comment on the matter, stating that Jepps is a private individual not involved in party politics.
Heather Mack, accused of murdering her mother in Bali, will transfer a significant portion of her trust fund to care for her four-month-old daughter, Stella. Mack, who is currently imprisoned in Bali, has been granted permission to keep Stella with her in her cell until the child turns two.  The transfer of funds comes after Mack claimed her uncle, the trustee of her estate, blocked her access to the money, and a judge ordered a portion of the funds be released for her defense and living expenses.
North Charleston police officer Michael Slager shot Walter Scott in the back, killing him, and then attempted to cover up the crime by planting his Taser near Scott's body and fabricating a story about a struggle.  The cover-up was exposed by a bystander's video, which contradicted the police's account of the incident.  Slager has been charged with murder, and questions remain about the culpability of other officers who were present at the scene and may have participated in the cover-up.
Wayne Rooney believes that Marouane Fellaini has transformed from a struggling player at Manchester United to a key attacking force, praising his ability to bring the ball down under pressure and create opportunities. Fellaini's recent success has been attributed to manager Louis van Gaal's tactical approach, which has allowed him to thrive as a second striker. Rooney also highlighted the team's improved form and preparation, attributing their recent success to hard work and detailed training sessions.
The FA Cup semi-finals, held at Wembley Stadium, provided compelling television viewing this weekend.  Both matches, featuring Arsenal vs. Reading and Liverpool vs. Aston Villa, were filled with drama and excitement, with the BBC and BT Sport delivering engaging coverage.  The coverage highlighted the emotional farewell of Liverpool captain Steven Gerrard, while also showcasing the passion and dedication of the players and fans, making for a truly memorable FA Cup weekend.
Reading, a Championship side, will face Arsenal in the FA Cup semi-final at Wembley, a historic occasion for the club as they haven't reached this stage in 88 years. Despite the excitement, manager Steve Clarke has urged his players to treat the game like any other, focusing solely on the task at hand and aiming for a win.  Clarke acknowledges Arsenal's strength and believes Reading will need to play a perfect game to overcome them, but remains confident in his team's ability to make history.
A severe HIV outbreak has been spreading in rural Indiana counties, primarily among users of the prescription opioid Opana. The outbreak has been linked to needle sharing, exacerbated by the drug's frequent injection requirements and the lack of access to healthcare resources in the area.  The CDC and state health officials are working to control the outbreak through education, needle exchange programs, and increased access to healthcare services.
Jeremy Clarkson will not face prosecution for assaulting a Top Gear producer, Oisin Tymon, after Tymon declined to press charges.  Despite the incident, Clarkson is still set to appear in Top Gear live shows alongside Richard Hammond and James May, while the future of the show itself remains uncertain.  The BBC has announced that Top Gear will likely continue in some form, but Hammond and May are not expected to return, and the show's future direction is unclear.
Six U.S. Navy guards have been charged with assaulting detainees at Camp Bucca in Iraq in May, following an investigation by the Army Criminal Investigation Division. The alleged incidents involved physical assaults on two detainees and the confinement of eight prisoners in a cell sprayed with riot control agent. The guards will face courts-martial, which are expected to begin within 30 days at Camp Bucca.
Dzhokhar Tsarnaev was found guilty on all counts for the Boston Marathon bombing and now faces the death penalty. The sentencing phase of the trial has begun, with victims and their families sharing their harrowing experiences and the lasting impact of the attacks. The prosecution is presenting evidence of Tsarnaev's lack of remorse and the cruelty of his actions, while victims describe the physical and emotional trauma they continue to endure.
Charlie Patino, an 11-year-old midfielder with exceptional talent, is attracting interest from Premier League giants Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham.  Like former Luton Town prodigy Jack Wilshere, Patino has impressed with his skills and footballing intelligence, leading to multiple offers from top clubs.  The Patino family, guided by Luton Town, are carefully considering the options and prioritizing their son's development, aiming to provide him with the best opportunity to pursue a professional football career.
A Bangkok Airways plane carrying 72 people crashed at Koh Samui airport in Thailand, killing the pilot and injuring 37 others. The ATR-72 turboprop skidded and crashed after landing, likely due to strong winds that air traffic control had warned the pilot about. Emergency responders are working to free the co-pilot who is trapped in the wreckage, while seven passengers sustained serious injuries.
Tottenham striker Emmanuel Adebayor has publicly stated his desire to stay at the club and fight for his place in the team, despite recent reports linking him with a move away.  Adebayor's playing time has been limited this season due to the emergence of Harry Kane, but he remains committed to seeing out his contract at White Hart Lane.  The 31-year-old Togolese forward expressed his gratitude for the opportunity to play in the Premier League, which he considers the best in the world.
